On the tutorial of setters and getters. Just for fun using PHPs magic methods:

<?php

class Movie {
    public $title;
    private $rating;
    private $ratings = ["G", "PG", "PG-13", "R"];

    public function __construct($title, $rating) {
        $this->title = $title;
        $this->rating = $rating;
    }

    public function __get($property) {
        if (property_exists($this, $property)) {
            return $this->$property;
        }
    }

    public function __set($property, $value) {
        if (property_exists($this, $property)) {
            if ($property === "rating") {
                $value = in_array($value, $this->ratings) ? $value : "NR";
            }

            $this->$property = $value;
        }

        return $this;
    }
}

$movie = new Movie("Avengers", "");
echo "$movie->title, $movie->rating\n";
$movie->title = "Avengers";
$movie->rating = "";
echo "$movie->title, $movie->rating\n";

?>

For PHP this won't work as intended since __set and __get are used only on inaccessible properties. In the constructor they happen to be accessible since they are properties of the class itself so they are not run, that's what I think anyways I'd love to be corrected. But later on when an instance has been made and you start accessing/modifying the private properties __get and __set are run.

So you can drop the constructor and only choose to add or modify private properties on an instance of the class. Maybe it would be better if PHP knew that you were modifying a private property during construction and as such should run the __get or __set methods. But I might be missing something as this may be possible but I just don't know how to do it in this language.

